loadPkg("xtable")
loadPkg("kableExtra")
loadPkg("stringi")

xkabledply = function(modelsmmrytable, title="Table", digits = 4, pos="left", bso="striped") { 
  #' Combining base::summary, xtable, and kableExtra, to easily display model summary. 
  #' wrapper for the base::summary function on model objects
  #' ELo 202004 GWU DATS
  #' version 1.2
  #' @param modelsmmrytable This can be a generic table, a model object such as lm(), or the summary of a model object summary(lm()) 
  #' @param title Title of table. 
  #' @param digits Number of digits to display
  #' @param pos Position of table, c("left","center","right") 
  #' @param bso bootstrap_options = c("basic", "striped", "bordered", "hover", "condensed", "responsive")
  #' @return HTML table for display
  #' @examples
  #' library("xt height = "300px"able")
  #' library("kableExtra")
  #' xkabledply( df, title="Table testing", pos="left", bso="hover" )
  modelsmmrytable %>%
    xtable() %>% 
    kable(caption = title, digits = digits) %>%
    kable_styling(bootstrap_options = bso, full_width = FALSE, position = pos) %>%
    kableExtra::scroll_box(width = "500px")
}

xkablesummary = function(df, title="Table: Statistics summary.", digits = 4, pos="left", bso="striped") { 
  #' Combining base::summary, xtable, and kableExtra, to easily display numeric variable summary of dataframes. 
  #' ELo 202004 GWU DATS
  #' version 1.2
  #' @param df The dataframe.
  #' @param title Title of table. 
  #' @param digits Number of digits to display
  #' @param pos Position of table, c("left","center","right") 
  #' @param bso bootstrap_options = c("basic", "striped", "bordered", "hover", "condensed", "responsive")
  #' @return The HTML summary table for display, or for knitr to process into other formats 
  #' @examples
  #' xkablesummary( faraway::ozone )
  #' xkablesummary( ISLR::Hitters, title="Five number summary", pos="left", bso="hover"  )
  
  s = summary(df) %>%
    apply( 2, function(x) stringr::str_remove_all(x,c("Min.\\s*:\\s*","1st Qu.\\s*:\\s*","Median\\s*:\\s*","Mean\\s*:\\s*","3rd Qu.\\s*:\\s*","Max.\\s*:\\s*")) ) %>% # replace all leading words
    apply( 2, function(x) stringr::str_trim(x, "right")) # trim trailing spaces left
  
  colnames(s) <- stringr::str_trim(colnames(s))
  
  if ( dim(s)[1] ==6 ) { rownames(s) <- c('Min','Q1','Median','Mean','Q3','Max') 
  } else if ( dim(s)[1] ==7 ) { rownames(s) <- c('Min','Q1','Median','Mean','Q3','Max','NA') }
  
  xkabledply(s, title=title, digits = digits, pos=pos, bso=bso )
}

xkablevif = function(model, title="VIFs of the model", digits = 3, pos="left", bso="striped", wide=FALSE) { 
  #' Combining faraway::vif, xtable, and kableExtra, to easily display numeric summary of VIFs for a model. 
  #' ELo 202004 GWU DATS
  #' version 1.2
  #' @param model The lm or compatible model object.
  #' @param title Title of table. 
  #' @param digits Number of digits to display
  #' @param pos Position of table, c("left","center","right") 
  #' @param bso bootstrap_options = c("basic", "striped", "bordered", "hover", "condensed", "responsive")
  #' @param wide print table in long (FALSE) format or wide (TRUE) format
  #' @return The HTML summary table of the VIFs for a model for display, or for knitr to process into other formats 
  #' @examples
  #' xkablevif( lm(Salary~Hits+RBI, data=ISLR::Hitters, wide=T ) )
  
  vifs = table( names(model$coefficients)[2:length(model$coefficients)] ) # remove intercept to set column names
  vifs[] = faraway::vif(model) # set the values
  if (wide) { vifs <- t(vifs) }
  xkabledply( vifs, title=title, digits = digits, pos=pos, bso=bso )
}

1 Introduction

In the 21st century, climate change has become recognized as a severe global issue. Climate change is a long-term change in the average weather patterns that have come to define Earths local, regional and global climates. These changes have a broad range of observed effects that are synonymous with the term. Human activities causing an increase in greenhouse gas emissions, fossil fuel burning in particular, are the driving cause of climate change and global warming. The average increase in global temperature between 1880 and 1981 was ~0.07C (0.13F); however, the average rate of increase since1981 (0.18C / 0.32F) has more than doubled. One method for combatting climate change is to increase the supply and use of renewable energy, particularly solar energy, which allows for the replacing of carbon-intensive energy sources and an overall significant reduction in greenhouse gas emissions. This paper aims to focus on the availability of solar panel implementations and the potential carbon-offsets that coincide with increased solar energy use.

The SMART questions we will be focusing on are:
1. Analyze: Which variables have the greatest effect on the total solar energy generation potential?
2. Determine: Which variables significantly effect the estimated carbon dioxide abatement?
3. Compare: How does the estimated mean solar energy generation per panel type vary by region.

Included in our discussion is some exploratory data analysis (EDA) focusing on cleaning the data and preparing it for model-use as well as some linear models and ANOVA tests use to help answer our SMART questions. We used multiple models to show the advantages of including certain variables and excluding others.

2 EDA

Our EDA began by reading in the csv file, removing the unnecessary columns, renaming columns for readability purposes, removing observations with missing data, and changing data types as needed. We then explored the data using histograms, box plots, bar plots, scatter plots, and a correlation plot to prepare for model-building. Our exploration results along with explanations can be found below.

3 Linear Models

Based on the previous EDA and correlation analysis, we picked the carbon offset potential as the dependent variable to build a linear model to determine effects of sunlight_total,panels_total,region and panels in all directions on Carbon offset. We are adding the independent variables step by step to find out the best model.

3.1 Model 1

Dependent Variables:
1. total solar energy generation potential
2. total number of solar panels

fit1 <- lm(carbon_offset ~ sunlight_total + panels_total, data = citydf1)
summary(fit1)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(fit1)

The model results show that model 1 has a high Multiple R-squared of 0.937, meaning 93.7% data can be explained by the model. Total solar energy generation potential has a negative (coef = -4.16310^{-4}) relationship with carbon offset, and a 0.306 relationship with carbon offset.

The residual plot looks fine but the cooks distance value is too high.

3.2 Model 2

Dependent Variables:
1. total solar energy generation potential
2. total number of solar panels
3. region

fit2 <- lm(carbon_offset ~ sunlight_total + panels_total + region, data = citydf1)
summary(fit2)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(fit2)

The model 2 adds the variable region, the results show that model 2 has a high Multiple R-squared of 0.94, meaning 94% data can be explained by the model. The relationship significance between total solar energy generation potential and carbon offset has increased to -3.73310^{-4}, and the relationship significance between total solar panel numbers and carbon offset has decreased to 0.292.

Looking at the region factor, all regions have a negative effect with carbon offset, and the West region has the most significant relationship with a coefficient value of -4.2210^{4}, and the Northeast region has the lowest significant relationship with a coefficient value of -1.99610^{4}.

The residuals plot of model 2 looks fine, the cooks distance has slightly improved compared with model 1 but still high.

3.3 Model 3

Dependent Variables:
1. total solar energy generation potential
2. total number of solar panels
3. regions
4. panel flat (highest correlation with carbon_offset)

fit3 <- lm(carbon_offset ~ sunlight_total + panels_total + region + panels_flat, data = citydf1)
summary(fit3)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(fit3)

The model 3 adds the variable total number of flat solar panels given that the flat angle panel has the highest correlation with the dependent variable carbon offset from previous analysis. The results show that model 3 also has a high Multiple R-squared of 0.94, meaning 94% data can be explained by the model. The variable panels_flat has a negative (coef = -0.001) relationship with carbon offset.

The residuals plot of model 3 looks fine, but the cooks distance value is way too high.

3.4 Model 4

Dependent Variables:
1. total solar energy generation potential
2. regions
3. all 5 panel directions
we remove panels_total from this model because it causes perfect multicollinearity.

fit4 <- lm(carbon_offset ~ sunlight_total + region + panels_flat + panels_north + panels_south + panels_east + panels_west, data = citydf1)
summary(fit4)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(fit4)

Based on the modeling work from model 1-3, in order to get the best model, we removed panels_total because it causes multicollinearity, and we added all 5 solar panel directions including flat to build model 4.

The results show that model 4 has the best Multiple R-squared so far at 0.95. The south-facing solar panels panels_south has the most significant relationship with carbon offset, with a coefficient value of 0.665, followed by east-facing panels with a coefficient value of 0.56. North- and West-facing panels have a negative influence on carbon offset, with coefficient values of -0.197 and -0.128 respectively.

The residuals plot of model 4 looks fine, and the cooks distance value finally looks good and its below 1.

5 Conclusion

5.1 Our Findings

From the above tests, we conclude that Model 4 is the best model to use for determining which variables have the greatest effects on Carbon offset. The p-value in Model 4 is < 0.05, and the multiple R-squared value is 95% which means the variables in the Model 4 can explain 95% of changes in the dataset. Cooks plot shows that there are some high influence points along with some other high leverage points, which matches the result in plots 2.5.3. This model shows that panels in the west region create the largest positive carbon emission abatement impact while panels in the northeast region have the lowest impact on carbon abatement. Our boxplots show that flat panels generate the most solar power energy across all regions while panels facing north generate the least amount of solar power across all regions. To summarize our findings, in general, flat panels in the west region of the US will generate the most solar power and have the greatest positive impact on carbon emission abatement.

5.2 Caveats

1. Our models have high multicollinearity. While building early models, we found high vif values and had to adjust the models multiple times to obtain desirable outcomes. Some variables were completely linearly dependent, so we had to remove them from our models to receive accurate results.
2. There are high outlier counts in the dataset. We observed this in the Total Potential Solar Energy Generated vs Region boxplot in the EDA section. We had to adjust the y-axis improve readability of the plots. This leads some missing data in our representations.
3. All the values in the dataset are estimated values obtained from the google database of imagery and maps. They are not real world recorded values obtained from readings of solar panels directly.
4. Since the carbon offset value was calculated by the Google Sunroof Project, we are not sure of the formula used. Our findings of certain panel types in certain regions having negative effects on carbon emission abatement might not be totally accurate in the long-term. We assume they would have a net-positive impact over their lifespan.
